## Problem1('32 31')
#  Approximate a cube root of a number close
#  to a perfect cube using linear approximation
#ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a1 = random(1,5,1);
$a2 = $a1*$a1*$a1;
$d1 = random(.1,.4,.1);
$b1 = $a2+$d1;
$m1 = (1/3)*$a2**(-2/3);
$y1 = $a1;
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Use linear approximation, i.e. the tangent line,  to approximate
\(  \sqrt[3] { $b1 } \) as follows: $BR
Let \( f(x) = \sqrt[3] x \).
The equation of the tangent line to \( f(x) \) at \( x = $a2 \)
can be written in the form \( y = mx+b \)
where \( m \) is: \{ans_rule(20) \}
EOT
$ans = $m1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
and  where \( b \) is: \{ans_rule(20) \} $BR
EOT
$ans = $y1 -$m1*$a2;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Using this, we find our approximation for \( \sqrt[3] {$b1} \) is
\{ans_rule(20) \}
EOT

$ans = $m1*$b1 + $y1 -$m1*$a2;
ANS(num_cmp($ans, relTol=>.00001));
ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
